The paper proposes a novel network for person re-identification that handles body part misalignment, which is a common problem in computer vision. The paper focuses on learning a part-aligned representation using a two-stream network and a bilinear-pooling layer. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses deep learning techniques to train the network, which suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also evaluates its approach on standard benchmark datasets, which suggests that it could belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. The paper also mentions that it does not require any part annotation on the person re-identification dataset, which suggests that it could belong to the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a new representation that leads to a robust image matching similarity, which suggests that it could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
